John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
The independent educational centres in Scotland have a career of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in the reviews that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes reaped in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (CIS) strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
The purpose of independent schools is to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desirable subject in the centres.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak a man in a language you understand, the message reaches his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, his heart reaches him."
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot depend solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can observe that the languages are at the highest of the classification tables, being the highest rates of approval in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students studying foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
Data collected from the 74 SCIS centres showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that the independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them a fundamental competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, as a subject, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the United Kingdom Employment and Skills Commission revealed that 17 % of the reasons given by employers about the difficulties they faced in filling jobs were attributed to the limited language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities requiring languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last his whole life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom in the face of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you will always be able to choose from several languages provided by specialized teachers in this area.
Scotland's independent educational centres devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and that teams with the skills needed to succeed, whatever their future.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered " competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We've got to do it right.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
