North Korea says that "there is no possibility" that they should be unilaterally disarmed first if they lack confidence
On Saturday, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of North Korea informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened its distrust in the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho declared before the annual General Assembly of the international agency that North Korea had adopted "significant measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as to stop carrying out nuclear and missile tests, dismantle nuclear testing facilities and commit to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
"If we do not trust the United States, we cannot have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances there is no possibility that we will first unilaterally disarm ourselves."
Although Ri repeated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a phased denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, its statement is important, since it did not simply reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim committed himself to working for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump ensured North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must renounce its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure by means of sanctions in order to achieve its purpose coercively, even by objecting to a declaration of termination of war," said Ri.
"The idea that sanctions can cause us to fall on our knees is a chemera of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our distrust."
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced by the US leader to the United Nations at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and Moon Jae, South Korea's leader in the last five months, and added: "If South Korea had been the focus of denuclearization rather than the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a standstill."
Even so, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year's speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to lead North Korea's missiles to American soil after the "evil president" Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim "a rocket man".
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in advancing towards disarmament, but said that much remained to be done and that sanctions needed to continue to be applied until North Korea became denuclearized.
