The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for the ballistic and nuclear missile programmes in Pyongyang.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would return to visit Pyongyang next month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea reported that his "requirements were those of a mobster."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the "related measures".
He said Kim had told him that the "appropriate measures" he was looking for were the security assurances Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to rest enough
Thanks to a new course this year at Harvard University, all university students sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing machistical culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found out that university students number one in the world usually have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine, and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, it is believed that the first of his class in the United States.
Their motivation to start the course arose after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl approached me and asked why she just learned about this now, in her last year.
He said no one had ever talked to him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
The course, delivered for the first time this year, explains the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were only sleeping during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression and cancer.
Afterwards, an icon on the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco," added Professor Czeisler.
He said that the culture of pride for "going the night sailing" still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure to which students are subjected meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and a good quality dream should be "the secret weapon" of students to fight stress, tiredness and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to create a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year in Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it to the entire campus.
She hoped that the next step would be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study programme before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler's recommendation is that students think about setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emit the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter the circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble sleeping.
