National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state of the Scottish Highlands, tries to find out how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything that is found is expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide the next conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common bats and sopranos, as well as the Daubenton river bats and long-eared browns of the gardens of Inverewe in Wester Ross.
Special tape recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of bat calls and what species they do.
A report and habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, expects the results to reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
The bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electric wiring can also pose a risk to them, as well as insecticides and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks of domestic cats.
The bats aren't really blind,
but because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the topic of bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in this field, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization has even inaugurated the first and only reserve dedicated to Scottish bats in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Three, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the proper habitat.
However, there are still many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop."
It stresses the importance of checking whether there are bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since an colony of offspring can be accidentally destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean eliminating a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to cooperate.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species that we don't know how their populations evolve."
