Red tide update: Decrease concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately along 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Unlawful plots can be found about 10 miles from the Hillsborough County coast, but in less places compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Easter County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in the County of Pinellas and at its coast, concentrations between low and high in the Coast of Hillsborough County, background to high in the County of Manatee, background to high in the County of Sarasota and its coast, background to medium in the County of Charlotte, background to high in the County of Lee and at its coast, and low concentrations in the County of Collier.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation problems in the northwest of Florida last week.
